Imagine a long web page with many sections (for example, a single-page HTML specification). If a user requests a specific section (such as page.html#section7), could the web server send that particular section first and then send the rest of the content later?
Stream order:
1. From the beginning of the HTML document to the <body> tag
2. The HTML code from Part 7
3. HTML code for Part 1, 2, 3, etc.
The browser should ensure that parts 1 to 6 are inserted above part 7 on the webpage.
Is this reasonable? Will it be useful?
My goal is to have the linked section (#section7) render as quickly as possible without having to reimplement it using JavaScript or similar technologies. I want a very long HTML document, but the linked section should still render quickly. This can be achieved simply with HTML.
The content can be streamed in this way, and then the browser will insert each <contents> element into the corresponding <div> element.
<div id="sec1"></div>
<div id="sec2"></div>
Etc.
<div id="sec7">section 7…</div>
<section id="sec1">Section 1…</section>
<section id="sec2">section 2…</section>
etc.
Although the order of streaming is out of sequence, the browser will assemble the HTML document in order.
@user22 Actually, you can rearrange the document content without using JavaScript. However, if you want the server to do something, you can't use the URL hash part anymore; instead, you should use query string parameters to let the server know which part you want to view first. As for rearranging the page content, you have the following options:
1. Use CSS
2. Using Templates with Slots
@user23 Right. The issue is that the visual order (what the user sees) and the DOM order are inconsistent. If HTML could support out-of-order streaming, and the browser could arrange the content in sequence into the DOM, that might be useful.
However, the slot method seems quite promising. I'll give it a try.
@user22 Oh, are you wanting the browser to automatically correct the DOM order?
@user23 You're right, that's exactly how I thought about it. The reason I transmitted the 7th part first is solely to allow users to see it as soon as possible. It would be great if we could achieve this without affecting the DOM order, so that the browser can ensure the final DOM order matches the visual order.
In other words, first transmit part 7, but the final result (DOM and visual effects) should be exactly the same as if all parts were transmitted in order.
@user22 @user33 You can check out PHOOOS without using JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
